COMPONENT NAME: IKM MSSQL Slowly Changing Dimension
AUTHOR: Oracle
Description: - Integration Knowledge Module - Management of TYPE 2 Slowly Changing Dimensions on Microsoft SQLServer. - Data can be controlled. Invalid data is isolated in the Error Table and can be recycled.
To use this Knowledge Module: When defining the Target Datastore, it is necessary to set the following parameters (from the "Slowly Changing Dimensions Behavior" list box, on the "Description" tab of each column concerned): - Surrogate Key: A single column identifying Records. This column must be defined as an Identity column on the Target Data Server and should be left unmapped. - Natural Key: Column(s) representing the Natural Key of the Record. - Overwrite Column: List of updatable column(s) (i.e. those that can be updated after modification of the original data). - Insert Row: List of column(s) representing the Slowly Changing Attributes (i.e. those that require a Record insert after modification of the original data) - Current Record Flag: A single numeric column mapped to 0 or 1 and representing the Current Record Flag status of the Record. It is automatically updated by the Knowledge Module (1 : Current Record ; 0 : Past Records) - Start Timestamp: A single date (or timestamp) column indicating the beginning of a Record's availability. E.g., "current_timestamp" as mapping expression. - End Timestamp: A single date (or timestamp) column indicating the end of the Record's availability. E.g. "'01 January 2400'" (single-quoted string)as mapping expression.
Restrictions: - Make sure to map ALL target table columns flagged as: "Surrogate Key", "Natural Key", "Current Record Flag", "Start Timestamp" and "End Timestamp". Notice that mappings set for the "Current Record Flag", "Start Timestamp" and "End Timestamp" columns are not used. - As this Knowledge Module is dedicated to Datawarehouse Projects (where data should not be removed), when using it with a journalized Source Datastore, it is not possible to synchronize deletions. Therefore, data should be manually filtered to exclude any source delete events (add a filter on JRN_FLAG = 'I'). - The TRUNCATE option cannot work if the target table is referenced by another table (i.e. with a Foreign Key). - Deletes are committed regardless of the COMMIT option. - The FLOW_CONTROL option calls the Check Knowledge Module to isolate invalid data. If the Table Primary Key is designated by the same column as the Surrogate Key, then: 1. On the "Diagram" tab of the Interface, uncheck the "Check Not Null" checkbox for the column representing the Primary Key. 2. On the "Control" tab of the Interface and in the "Constraint" panel, set the option value to NO for the Primary Key control.
Commit all data inserted or updated in the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to perform flow control.
Check this option to recycle data rejected by flow control in a previous execution of this interface.
Check this option to control the target table after having inserted or updated target data.
Check this option if you wish to truncate the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to delete all the rows of the target datastore.
Check this option if you wish to create the target table
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
Check this option if you wish to analyze the target table before loading data into the integration table.
This option generates an extra validation step. This step check that at least one column is marked as SCD_ADD and at least another one marked as SCD_UPD.
This option enables/disables index creation on flow table.
